Joint Retrieval of Aerosol Optical Depth and

Surface Reflectance Over Land Using

Geostationary Satellite Data

Lu She , Yong Xue , Senior Member, IEEE , Xihua Yang, John Leys, Jie Guang , Yahui Che,

Cheng Fan, Yanqing Xie , and Ying Li

Abstract — The   advanced   Himawari   imager   (AHI)   aboard the  Himawari-8  geostationary  satellite  provides  high-frequency observations  with  broad  coverage,  multiple  spectral  channels, and  high  spatial  resolution.  In  this  paper,  AHI  data  were  used to  develop  an  algorithm  for  joint  retrieval  of  aerosol  optical depth (AOD) over land and land surface bidirectional reflectance. Instead of performing surface reflectance estimation before calcu- lating AOD, the AOD and surface bidirectional reflectance were retrieved  simultaneously  using  an  optimal  estimation  method. The  algorithm  uses  an  atmospheric  radiative  transfer  model coupled  with  a  surface  bidirectional  reflectance  factor  (BRF) model.  Based  on  the  assumption  that  the  surface  bidirectional reflective  properties  are  invariant  during  a  short  time  period (i.e., a day), multiple temporal AHI observations were combined to calculate the AOD and surface BRF. The algorithm was tested over  East  Asia  for  year  2016,  and  the  AOD  retrieval  results were validated against the aerosol robotic network (AERONET) sites  observation  and  compared  with  the  Moderate  Resolution

I. I NTRODUCTION A EROSOLS are liquid and solid particles suspended in the atmosphere, which play an important role in influ- encing the earth’s radiation balance, hydrological cycle, and biogeochemical cycles [1]–[4]. It is considered that aerosols are one of the largest sources of uncertainty in global radiative forcing estimation [5]. Furthermore, aerosols have severe effects on human health and air quality, especially in urban region, more fine-mode aerosols were emitted [6]. Although we can obtain accurate aerosol information from ground-based measurements, these cannot meet the needs of long-term studies of aerosols on the global scale. Satellite data provide an effective way to obtain information about the spatiotemporal distribution of aerosols.

Spectral aerosol optical depth (AOD) is one of the most important parameters in the study of atmospheric pollution and aerosol’s radiative effects. It is used to quantify the extinction (including scattering and absorption) of solar radiation due to atmospheric aerosols. The quantitative measurement of AOD using satellite observations started more than 40

Spectral aerosol optical depth (AOD) is one of the most important parameters in the study of atmospheric pollution and aerosol’s radiative effects. It is used to quantify the extinction (including scattering and absorption) of solar radiation due to atmospheric aerosols. The quantitative measurement of AOD using satellite observations started more than 40 years ago [7]. However, it is still a challenging task to retrieve AOD over land due to the difficulty of separating the con- tribution of atmospheric aerosols from land signals received by the satellite at the top of atmosphere (TOA) [7], [8]. Numerous aerosol retrieval algorithms have been developed and applied to both polar-orbiting and geostationary satellite observations [7], [8]. Similar approaches based on the relati onships of spectral reflectance have also been widely applied to multispectral data such as the Medium Resolution Ima ging Spectrometer (MERIS) data [14] and even the data from a senor pair [15]. Another method based on a dynamical spectral surface reflectance model has been applied to sea- viewing wide field-of-view sensor (SeaWiFS) and MERIS [16], [17]. For bright surfaces, the structure function algorithm was applied to thematic mapper and Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer data [18], [19]. Hsu et al. [20], [21] suggested the “deep blue” (DB) algorithm for MODIS and SeaWiFS data using a precalculated static surface reflectance database, based on the fact that the reflectance of a bright surface in the near- UV and DB channels is very low. They further developed a hybrid method by combing the surface reflectance database and normalized difference vegetation index, as well as utilizing the relationships between visible (blue and red channels) and near-infrared (NIR) channels (0.86 and 2.1 μ m) [22]. Those methods often are based on the assumption of Lambert surfaces.

Geostationary satellites with high-frequency observations and large spatial coverage are capable of tracking aerosol’s movements and obtaining aerosol diurnal cycle. This ability is very helpful for monitoring air quality and estimating aerosol’s radiative forcing. For geostationary observations, the clear-sky reflectance composite approach is quite pop- ular,  such  as  with  Geostationary  Operational  Environ- mental Satellites (GOES)/advanced baseline imager [31], MTSAT-1R [32], Communication Ocean and Meteorological Satellite-1 (COMS-1)/geostationary ocean color imager) [33], COMS-1/meteorological imag er [34], and Meteosat Second Generation [35]. These algorithms are based on the assump- tion that the surface reflectance is invariant during a certain time period,

These algorithms are based on the assump- tion that the surface reflectance is invariant during a certain time period, e.g., 14 days. The second darkest reflectance for each pixel during the given time period is chosen and used to create a composite of reference surface reflectance images for aerosol retrieval. However, due to the rapid growth of vegetation and the change of surface moisture and sun position, the surface reflectance may change significantly, which can lead to inaccurate inve rsion results. Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA) launched the new gen- eration geostationary satellite Himawari-8 on October 7, 2014, and it started operation on July 7, 2015. Unlike traditional geostationary satellites with limited channels and relatively lower spatial resolution, Himawari-8 carries a new sensor called advanced Himawari imager (AHI). AHI can provide multispectral images with high spatial and temporal resolu- tion. With these characteristics, the AHI data have significant advantages for monitoring air quality and estimating aerosol properties.

In this paper, we present a novel method for obtaining hourly AOD using multitemporal AHI visible (VIS) radiance measurements. The algorithm i s based on the assumption that the aerosol properties are temporally variable, while the land surface BRF remains unchanged during a short period of time. The high temporal resolution AODs are obtained using an optimal estimation method. Section II gives a brief introduc- tion to the data we used. Section III describes the detail

AHI observation has a spatial coverage of 150° by 150°, and centered at 0° N, 140° E with a spatial resolution of 0.5–2 km for different channels at the subsatellite point. AHI provides a full-disk observation every 10 min, which provides data to

In this paper, the VIS channels’ data are used for the AOD retrieval. The AHI level 2 calibrated data and navigation data (including latitude, longitude, solar and sensor zenith angle, and azimuth angle) were coll ected. JMA freely distributes aerosol products retrieved from AHI, which provides AOD at 550 nm with a 5 km spatial resolution. The temporal resolution is 10 min for level 2 product, and 1 h for level 3 product. In this paper, level 2 AOD are used for comparing with our retrieval (hereafter, referred to “JMA AOD” in this paper) as it provides a finer temporal resolution to collocate the ground observed AOD data. Both the satellite observation and AOD product are obtained from the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency Earth Observation Research Center, which are provided by JMA (http://www.eorc.jaxa.jp/ptree/terms.html).

B. MODIS Aerosol Products

MODIS Collection 6 (C6) aerosol products are used to compare with the retrieved AODs. The current C6 aerosol product provides AOD from DT and DB algorithms, and a “combined” AOD data set from these two algorithms [13]. MODIS C6 AOD product (DB, DT, and the combined) have been intensively evaluated at both regional and global scale [41], [42]. According to Levy et al. [13] the MODIS C6 DT AOD over land has expected errors (EEs) of ± ( 0 . 05 + 0 . 15 τ A ) , where τ A refers to the aerosol robotic network (AERONET) measured AOD. While for DB AOD, a prognostic uncertainty is provided with EE =± ( 0 . 03 + 0 . 2 τ DB ) [42]. In this paper, AOD from both DT and DB was used for comparison to provide a better spatial coverage.

Sun photometer measured AOD from AERONET stations was used for the evaluation of the retrieved AOD from AHI. AERONET sites provide AOD at seven channels (340, 380, 440, 500, 675, 870, and 1020 nm) and with low uncer- tainty. The observations are taken under cloud-free conditions, and with a temporal resolution of 15 min. The most used

B. Surface BRDF Model

The surface reflectance is the most important part to achieve the retrieval. We adopted a semiempirical kernel-driven BRDF model to simulate the surface directional reflectance. Ross- thick–li-sparse (RTLS) model is one of the most acknowledged and widely used methods to describe BRDF. It has also been applied in the MODIS operational BRDF/Albedo product (MCD43) [46]. In the RTLS model, the land surface BRDF is simulated as the sum of three angular kernels representing the basic scattering process: isotropic, geometric optical, and volume scattering components [47]–[50]

IV. I NVERSE M ETHOD Instead of retrieving AOD after surface reflectance esti- mation, the AOD and surface BRF kernel coefficients are estimated simultaneously by an iteration process. To make the ill-posed inversion problem doable, two general assumptions are made: 1) the surface BRF is invariant during a short time period, while the AOD does change (e.g., 1 day) and 2) the AHI spectral BRDF shape [determined by f vol / f iso and f geo / f iso in (9)] can be obtained from the corresponding MODIS BRDF product, while only the f iso (λ) (isotropic kernel) coefficient varies from the MODIS product due to their slight differences in spectral response and acquisition time. Thus, with a fixed BRDF shape, AOD and the BRDF isotropic coefficient can be obtained using AHI multiple temporal observations. V. R ESULTS AND A NALYSIS We applied this algorithm to AHI data to estimate hourly AOD over the mainland China region over a whole year in 2016, as China has been suffering from serious air pollution due to the large amounts of Particulate Matter emissions. In this Section, we focus on comparing the AHI-derived AOD with AERONET measurements and MODIS C6 AOD. In addition, the JMA AOD and MODIS C6 AOD during the same time period were also evaluated using AERONET AOD.

The AHI obtained AODs (AHI AOD) at 550 nm were also compared with the MODIS C6 and JMA AOD products. In these images, AODs retrieved using our algorithm (a) and (d) show a similar aerosol distribution with that of the MODIS AOD products (b) and (e). VI. C ONCLUSION This paper presents a novel algorithm to retrieve AOD over land using AHI data. A non-Lambertian forward model cou- pled a surface BRDF model was employed in this algorithm. Based on the assumption that the land surface BRDF is stable for a short time period and that the surface BRDF shape has limited variation among different spectral ranges and in a short time period, the MODIS BRDF/albedo product was employed to provide the BRDF shape information for AHI visible channels and the prior information for AHI non-shape BRDF parameter (i.e., the isotropic coefficient). With multiple

temporal observations, the AODs were retrieved using an optimal estimation method through an iteration process. This method is proven applicable for different land surface types including both dark and bright land surfaces.

The retrieval results from one year of AHI data were evalu- ated against the ground-based AERONET measurements, and qualitatively compared with the MODIS C6 aerosol product. The JMA AODs and MODIS C6 AOD from both DT and DB during the same time period were also collected and validated against AERONET AODs, and the validation results were compared with our results. The retrieval results from one year of AHI data were evalu- ated against the ground-based AERONET measurements, and qualitatively compared with the MODIS C6 aerosol product. The JMA AODs and MODIS C6 AOD from both DT and DB during the same time period were also collected and validated against AERONET AODs, and the validation results were compared with our results. The AHI AODs show good agreement with AERONET measur ements, with a high corre- lation coefficient of 0.88, and 69.9% retrieval falling within the uncertainty of AOD =± 0 . 2 × AOD AERONET ± 0 . 05, which is better than that of JMA AOD (0.82 and 57.6%). The retrieved AHI AOD shows comparable accuracy with MODIS C6 AOD. The validation in three different regions shows noticeable difference: better performance was observed over north China and Korean peninsula, while underestimation was found at Southeast Asia. The AHI AOD and MODIS AOD generally show similar spatial distribution. And AHI-derived AOD can provide better spatial and temporal coverage for regional aerosol study than MODIS AOD. This algorithm has been proven to be able to characterize the temporal and spatial distribution of aerosols. This algorithm can also be used in other satellite data which have similar channels with AHI data, such as data from Fengyun-4 data, Himawari-9, and GOES-R. The retrieved AOD shows great potential in monitoring the air pollution with high temporal resolution to capture the spatial– temporal variations of local pollution.

Additional work is still required to address several issues. First, considering the importance of aerosol type, more analy- sis about aerosol models and model selection should be conducted in further work. Second, a more stable and accurate prior information about BRDF shape are required. Currently only two years of MODIS BRDF product were used for obtain- ing the BRDF shape, and it may be insufficient, especially for Southeast Asia. This will be solved by extending the MODIS data set and strictly screening it before use. Third, this method is also suitable for surface reflectance estimation using multi- channel and high-frequency observations, and related work on evaluation of surface reflectance results will be discussed in a separate paper.
